quot; (sh as in shiva, shrI etc, Sh as in uShA, veSha etc, s as in sa=\r\ntya, sama) is very similar to that of &quot;cha Ta ta&quot;. In the latter 3 sounds, =\r\ntongue touches the upper palate of mouth at 3 places (for which you just go=\r\nt a feel). In the former 3 sounds, tongue comes close to touching in the sa=\r\nme 3 places, but does not actually touch. It comes close to touching and th=\r\nere is some gap.\n=A0\nWith this understanding, now practice saying &quot;cha sha&quot;=\r\n several times, &quot;Ta Sha&quot; several times and &quot;ta sa&quot; several times. You will =\r\nsee that each pair is pronounced at the same place. If tongue touches mouth=\r\n&#39;s upper palate at one position for the first sound and comes close to touc=\r\nhing at a *different* position for the second sound in the same pair, you a=\r\nre making a mistake. Try again.\n=A0\nNo wonder that visarga becomes sh, Sh a=\r\nnd s if ch, T and t (respectively) come after it, as per sandhi rules of gr=\r\nammar. Sanskrit grammar is very logical and based on phonology (study of so=\r\nunds).\n=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstrology & Spirituality Resour=\r\nces: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n--------\r\n--61789334-714196421-1366581867=:17132\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=iso-8859-1\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color:#000; background-color:#fff; font-family:ar=\r\nial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size:10pt&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span&gt;Namaste friends,&lt;br&gt;&=\r\nnbsp;&lt;br&gt;Some people are confused with the &quot;sh&quot; sound as in &quot;shiva&quot; or &quot;shr=\r\nI rAma&quot; or &quot;shava&quot;. I want to clarify it.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;There are three s-so=\r\nunds in Sanskrita - sha, Sha and sa (using iTrans notation). They appear in=\r\n alphabet in that order. The middle one is written in Devanagari script lik=\r\ne &quot;pa&quot; with a cross line through it. The first let